  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is a multi-volume octavo work by Georges Cuvier (1769–1832) surveying the progress of the natural sciences from the year of the French Revolution (1789) to the mid-1820s. It represents the expanded book form of Cuvier's official reports on scientific progress, originally commissioned by Napoleon and later continued under the Bourbon Restoration monarchs Louis XVIII and Charles X. Published by Baudouin Frères in Paris between 1826 and 1828, the work is a landmark in the historiography of science, written by the man who was simultaneously the most powerful scientific administrator in France and one of its greatest naturalists.",
